               <p>SECOND COUNT, the same, only omitting the words in italics.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-284-person2656">
                  ADEY 
                  BELLAMY SAVORY
               <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2656" type="surname" value="BELLAMY SAVORY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2656" type="given" value="ADEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2656" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a 
               <persName id="t18290910-284-person2657">
                  dealer 
                  in bullion
               <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2657" type="surname" value="in bullion"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2657" type="given" value="dealer"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2657" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and live at No. 14, <placeName id="t18290910-284-crimeloc1568">Cornhill</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-284-crimeloc1568" type="placeName" value="Cornhill"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-284-crimeloc1568" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-284-off1565 t18290910-284-crimeloc1568"></join>. I had forty-five Napoleons on the 20th of July, and twenty-eight of them were taken; I had not noticed them very particularly; I deal in money generally - they were taken from my son; I was present, but did not see them taken; they were usually kept in a drawer, or in a bowl in the window.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-284-person2658">
                  JOSEPH 
                  SAVORY
               <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2658" type="surname" value="SAVORY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2658" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2658" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prosecutor's son. On the 20th of July a person came into the shop and asked for 50l. worth of French money - I counted out forty-five Napoleons into my hand and laid them on the counter; I turned to my desk to reckon what they would come to, and the person who came for them said he would step into Birch's and take something while I made the account; the prisoner then came in, seized a handful of the Napoleons, and ran off - I called my father from the back shop, and jumped over the counter - I pursued the prisoner down Pope's Head-alley and Lombard-street to the Mansion-house; a person I knew, of the name of Finch, was coming by, he saw I could hardly catch him, he caught him, and brought him back - the prisoner was running: Finch is not here; I took the prisoner to our counting-house, and went back to Pope's Head-alley to look for one Napoleon he had dropped, but it was gone; he had the rest of the money on him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. Were they in your possession? A. They were on the counter close before me; I did lose sight of the person who took them for perhaps half a minute or a quarter of a minute - he ran two hundred or two hundred and fifty yards before he was taken; it was about five o'clock - there were a great number of persons about - our dwelling-house is in the parish of St. Michael, Cornhill; the Napoleons were within half a yard of me - they had not been paid for.</p>

               <p>COURT. Q. Had there been any bargain between you? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-284-person2659">
                  WILLIAM 
                  WORCESTER
               <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2659" type="surname" value="WORCESTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2659" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2659" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner at the shop<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182909100145"></xptr>a quarter before five o'clock; I saw the witness coming with him - I went and searched his person; he said, "They are in this pocket;" and took twenty-five Napoleons out of his right-hand pocket, and put them into my hand; I felt in his pocket and found one more, and one was found on the mat of the door - one I understood was lost.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Is the property in Court?</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-284-person2660">
                  JOSEPH 
                  SAVORY
               <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2660" type="surname" value="SAVORY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2660" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-person2660" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . No; the gentleman came in again for it and had it - he was a most respectable man.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Is this a dwelling-house? A. There is a watchman sleeps there; there is a bed, but we do not use it.</p>
               <p>Four witnesses gave the prisoner a good character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY - <rs id="t18290910-284-punish1569" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290910-284-punish1569" type="punishmentCategory" value="death"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-284-defend2653 t18290910-284-punish1569"></join>
               DEATH
            </rs>. Aged 27.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290910-284-verdict1570" type="verdictDescription">
